<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06032229 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06032229 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; U.S. ALLIES PLEDGE $40 BILLION MORE; Washington -- Under pressure fromthe Bush administration and cries of outrage from Congress, the United States'allies are ponying up more money to help pay for the Persian Gulf war.; In thelast two weeks, as the costs have soared, the allies have pledged $40 billionmore for the first three months of this year to defray military and othercosts of the conflict.; MOTHER-TO-BE GETS A WELL-TIMED CALL; Chicago -- Of allthe servicemen and women trying to call home from the Persian Gulf these days,Army Sgt. William Lohrman had the best timing.; Earlier this week, Lohrman'swife, Connie, 20, was in labor with their first child at St. Joseph MedicalCenter in Joliet, Ill., when the nurse handed her the phone.; &quot;Somebody said,'How are you doing?' I said, 'I'm hurting. Who's this?' He said, 'It's Billy,your husband.' &quot; Mom and child are doing well.; GIS TAKE OVER DRIVING SUPPLIESTO FIGHTERS; Near The Iraqi Border -- The Army is flying in thousands ofsoldiers from the United States to take over the trucking of supplies tofront-line troops because local drivers have refused to go into a combatzone.; Associated Press; PRO-SADDAM -- Jordanians rally today in Amman after aclergyman urged Muslims to participate in a 'holy war' against U.S.-led forcesin the gulf.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; KUWAIT; US; MIDEAST; WAR; NEWS; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Top Soviet military officials, who are following every blow struck in thePersian Gulf war, say the United States significantly underestimated thedefensive and offensive capability of Iraq and is in for a long and difficultconflict. &quot;The Americans obviously underestimated Saddam Hussein,&quot; said Lt.Gen. German S. Starodubov. &quot;They thought that after the first bombardments, hewould either capitulate, or rush headlong into some kind of risky escapade,&quot;Starodubov told the Communist Party weekly Glasnost. &quot;But hardly could that beexpected from an opponent who had just fought in the desert for eight years&quot;against Iran.;   ISRAELIS ARE BLAMING GERMANS FOR SCUDS  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOVIETS PREDICTING LONG, DIFFICULT WAR  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  War in the GulfSee related stories pages 1A and 14-16A of this section.Mideast Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     Jerusalem -- With each Iraqi missile attack, Israelis grow angrier withGermany for helping Saddam Hussein build his war machine. Many feel theGermans never learned the lesson of the Holocaust.;    &quot;When we sit at nightwith our gas masks on, and think that Germany is again involved in an attemptto kill Jews with gas, we feel very bitter,&quot; said Labor Party lawmaker ChaimRamon, who lost relatives in the Holocaust.;    The first Scud missile attackon Israel Jan. 18 ignited anti-German passions, and they have been furtherinflamed by reports that German scientists extended the range of Iraq's Scudmissiles and helped make Iraqi war chemicals.;    But the angry mood hascreated a dilemma. Israel can't afford to go against public opinion, but italso can't afford to reject the millions of dollars in aid Germany has offeredin a belated attempt to patch up relations.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Moscow  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910201  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  496  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday February 1, 199100032229,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>